ica / rWilliams, Carolyn -- t10. "Let Your Names Be Enrolled": Method And Ideology In Women's Antislavery Petitioning / rVan Broekhoven, Deborah Bingham -- t11. Graphic Discord: Abolitionist And Antiabolitionist Images / rLapsansky, Phillip -- t12. Abby Kelley And The Process Of Liberation / rMelder, Keith -- t13. "A Good Work Among The People": The Political Culture Of The Boston Antislavery Fair / rChambers-Schiller, Lee -- t14. By Moral Force Alone: The Antislavery Women And Nonresistance / rBacon, Margaret Hope -- t15. "Women Who Speak For An Entire Nation": American And British Women At The World Anti-Slavery Convention, London, 1840 / rSklar, Kathryn Kish -- tBibliographical Notes -- tNotes On Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA small group of black and white American women who banded together in the 1830s and 1840s to remedy the evils of slavery and racism, the "antislavery females" included many who ultimately struggled for equal rights for women as well. Organizing fundraising fairs, writing pamphlets and giftbooks, circulating petitions, even speaking before "promiscuous" audiences including men and women-the antislavery women energetically created a diverse and dynamic political culture. A lively exploration of this nineteenth-century reform movement, The Abolitionist Sisterhood includes chapters on the principal female antislavery societies, discussions of black women's political culture in the antebellum North, articles on the strategies and tactics the antislavery women devised, a pictorial essay presenting rare graphics from both sides of abolitionist debates, and a final chapter comparing the experiences of the American and British women who attended the 1840 World Anti-Slavery Convention in London.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publishe